        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Hello, I have a major infrastructure upgrade due shortly, and I'm wondering if now is the time to instead consider switching to Cloud services for all or part, rather than follow the more traditional path (which I've done several times).<br /><br />This may go to the heart of whether the IT industry is headed in this direction, or is already there.<br /><br />For background I'm talking: 1000 users, 20TB of data, two data centres, application level data replication across these data centres (DFS-R, Exchange CCR, SQL Mirroring), a mix of VMware and physicals, traditional SAN, netbackup to tape silo. Very few business apps, mostly email, file, print. No regional sites, all well connected min 1gb/s.  All circa 2008 tech and all soon due for replacement. PCs are all standard win7 office 2007.<br /><br />Should I consider a cautious upgrade to some Cloud services? A radical move of everything to the cloud? Will users revolt? Has anyone else been in this place and thought this through? <br /><br />Thanks

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
