        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">Specit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm talking: 1000 users, 20TB of data, two data centres, application level data replication across these data centres (DFS-R, Exchange CCR, SQL Mirroring), a mix of VMware and physicals, traditional SAN, netbackup to tape silo. Very few business apps, mostly email, file, print. No regional sites, all well connected min 1gb/s.  All circa 2008 tech and all soon due for replacement. PCs are all standard win7 office 2007.</div><br />As a guess, you probably have enough equipment in place that a migration to an external cloud will be more costly than keeping it in-house.  I believe the two big differences are likely to be uptime (how good is your DR plan?) and security.  Also, as previously mentioned, be sure that any compliance regulations are followed (easier to verify for in-house).   Finally, please remember to check the customer service aspect of the cloud service (both to admins and to users).<br /><br />Considering the changes in server capabilities in the past few years, you should probably look into increasing your level of virtualization (cut down on the number of physical servers).  The net result should be a smaller footprint, with lower power and cooling requirements.<br /><br />You might also be able to do some sort of desktop virtualization.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
