        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              From my experience the specifics of Cloud migration come down to three factors, corporate security policy, budget and user performance expatiations.  As you’ve no doubt discovered in your search for an answer, the best solution involves considerable analysis on your part- and that’s a good thing.  Few organizations have been happy with the “put everything in the cloud” approach.  Your investment in planning is critical to successfully make what will probably be the single most complex and important change to your IT environment.<br /><br />One approach that works well is to deconstruct all assumptions about how to host IT services, especially those that have been long considered sacred.  In your example, you mentioned moving your Exchange systems to the cloud.  If you’re going to do that and accept the implied total dependence on your WAN link for even inter-office email, do you want to manage servers at all?  Would a hosted Exchange platform be a better choice?  Latency-tolerant storage is a no-brainer.  Cloud storage is cheap and good.<br /><br />It will depend on your organization, but breaking long running services into their base features in a matrix will help.  In the Exchange example it’s pretty simple: users connect via fat Outlook, mobile and OWA to Exchange in the sky. If those are your functional requirements then the specifics of the implementation are wide open and you can consider many more options than just pushing your Exchange infrastructure onto AWS/Rackspace hosts.  If you have multiple services integrated into AD authentication providers linked to your Exchange, then those should be additional requirements in your matrix.<br /><br />Policy will also set some limits.  Legal may, for whatever unfathomable reason they choose, throw up a wall of objections to some data being stored outside the premises.  A cloud provider may have a perfectly acceptable solution, but your time investment to get sign-off may eclipse the actual technical migration.  In that case you may elect to keep some systems on premises.  The great news is that all major cloud providers provide extended network solutions to allow interoperability between on-site and cloud hosted systems.<br /><br />Which brings me to my final recommendation- monitoring.  As we’ve seen several times in the last six months, cloud provider DevOps at AWS, Microsoft and others have killed customer environments.  Worse they haven’t had timely answers when parts of those environments have been broken, and your management will demand the same level of infrastructure awareness as you have with on-site gear.  “This is all the AWS dashboard tells me”, won’t be an answer that builds faith in your cloud migration project.  Make sure you’ve implemented your own network and systems monitoring for <span style="font-style: italic">all </span>cloud systems just as you do today in your local hardware and apps.  There is no substitute for blinking lights, reports and charts.<br /><br />It’s a great time for IT, Good luck!  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/smile.png" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> <br /><br />Patrick Hubbard, Head Geek, <a href="http://www.solarwinds.com" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">SolarWinds</a>

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
