        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              With 1000 users, you may find gmail and Google docs don't give you the manageability and features you expect.  There's a reason Microsoft earns billions on Exchange/Outlook (Office)- it's pretty good.  If your users have been on it for some time, especially if they use group collaboration features like the calendar, integrated AD for SharePoint, common access control using AD groups, meeting room assignment, they may not be happy with a move to Google services.  Additionally, recent changes to Google office should make you consider the possibility they may make changes to the offering that put you in a bind down the road.<br /><br />The great news there is you can keep all your users on fat Office clients, and invisibly relocate your mail service to the cloud, either to a hosted Exchange provider where they do everything for you in a SaaS model and you pay per user, or you move your existing environment to the cloud.  There are trade-offs to both.  Latency as a user experience issue will continue to be more a factor of the speed of the back-end system interconnections, not the &quot;last mile&quot; between the Exchange Transport Role, or Mail Store service and users Outlook clients.  In many cases you can actually get a performances boost on the back-end with cloud vs. older gear sitting in your data center.  <br /><br />On the storage side, there's no way around noticeable dings to file share performance of cloud vs. a local NAS or SAN.  Light only moves so fast, and routers are busy. Properly implemented however it may not be too bad, and there are some great solutions to make it easier.  Proxies are available that connect your LAN to cloud storage, and allow you to present normal enough looking file shares just has you have today.  Many also integrate with your directory services (AD or LDAP) allowing you to maintain RBAC even though the &quot;share&quot; lives on the cloud. <br /><br />For your n-tier you're already using virtualization, so it will come down how tightly connected they need to be.  If most of your network traffic in the data center is inter-server (Ex: web based apps talking to databases from Apache/IIS), as long as you push the whole pile to the cloud, performance shouldn't suffer.  The great thing about VMware is you can now find cloud providers who offer cloud VMware hosting, so you can transport VMs you already have.<br /><br />As for backup, that's one place you should absolutely consider cloud.  Services like S3 and Glacier are great examples, and offer 500 mile DR, multi-site replication, business continuity and cost advantages.  Basic S3 can look a lot like a remote file share and Glacier is 1/10th the price using tape backend.  It's slow to read, but for backups if you just need to write the data daily and only recover in a rare emergency, it's good.<br /><br />One thing you will spend more on is your WAN connection.  You'll need not just more bandwidth, but low-latency connections and traffic optimization.  You may need to upgrade your edge and firewall hardware to ensure smooth service and look into CBQoS and other traffic policy tools.  Of course NetFlow is also a must to make sure your critical cloud hosted apps aren't killed by YouTube traffic.  Also, some ISPs may have shorter routes to your cloud provider.<br /><br />The great thing with cloud projects today is many other folks have done it- it’s no longer just being edge, thought leadership noise from vendors.  Google is your friend, and there are some great &quot;wow I learned about the cloud from that&quot; blogs out there.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
