              <div class="quotetitle">andyfatbastard wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think there's something to be said for dipping your toe in the cloudy waters. There's probably quite a few non-essential systems you are hosting yourself that would be really good candidates for a cloud service instead. Moving everything off in one lump is a pretty bad idea, as there's quite a lot of adjustments to be made.</div><br /><br />The OP didn't specify whether the data centers were in-house or co-lo, and projections for growth or decline (especially with virtualization) of hardware footprint, but generally this is the strategy. Segregate which functions can or should be performed by SaaS or genetic outsourced services, which can move to an IaaS cloud, and how difficult it would be to put those services into an outsourced VMware farm versus a more advanced and highly abstracted SOA infrastructure like AWS.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Specit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I can see that apps need to be latency and probably bandwidth tolerant to ensure success. I may need to do some testing to see if users would be happy with something like gmail in a browser, as opposed to perhaps keeping outlook and going office 365. I've read that gmail via outlook is painful.</div><br /><br />Microsoft works hard to maintain the interdependence of its Office-Outlook and Exchange pairing. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Is there any acceptable cloud based equivalent of mapped drives and file shares though? Does google drive cut it, or would hosted sharepoint be more functional (and complex)?</div><br /><br />To best manage data you want it in an application, not free-form, where possible. In other words, a CRM or even a CMS instead of a shared drive that endlessly accumulates files that are inherently less well organised than a database.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Other business apps I anticipate will be the trickiest. For the traditional n-tier app I may need to keep SQL close to the middle/business logic tier, but use a browser front end to that. I'm thinking a hosted VMs may be better there. AWS or Azure maybe. Or I just keep that in house on VMware. But then I'm back in the business of dealing with SANs and Netbackup which I'd dearly love to see the end of.</div><br /><br />It seems like you should approach this by defining those things which you most want to de-complexify (storage and backups, or merely the proliferation and faults of your chosen solutions?) and existing capital assets like cooled datacenter square footage and network infrastructure.

              

              
              
            </div>
