        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Thanks for all the tips everyone, basically what I've taken away is:<br /><br />1. A cautious and partial Cloud migration may be best.<br />2. Focus on the Internet/WAN, latency, routing, etc. Stop YouTube from bringing down email. Stop a single huge email attachment from knocking out critical services.<br />3. Plan for the *next* move, away from this Cloud provider to the next. I.e. in case of issues, a rapid move is best.<br />4. Ensure the data ownership, regulatory issues are ok.<br />5. Go cloud backup (I'm still uncertain who is in the market here though, and how this works). <br />6. Possibly keep the MS Fat clients that users are accustomed too. Which may mean Office 365. <br />7. Virtualise everything else. Consider a cloud VMware provider.<br />8. Monitor everything in the cloud with the same (or more?) intensity that we do now for in house stuff.<br />9. Contract management is key (but tricky with the big players who may be ambivalent to such a small customer. A financial penalty for non performance may just give us a refund of the very small part monthly fee). <br /><br />Did I miss anything?

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
     
